						               													<description>Fitting the mold of 1980's vintage trivia games of the, &amp;quot;A Bit O' Blarney&amp;quot; challenges its players with the literature, geography, history, legends, and other cultural aspects of Ireland. Players draw a card for their question number, choose a category, try to answer the matching question in the book, and -- if successful -- roll the die, advance, and repeat the procedure. A wrong answer ends the player's turn. Some spaces on the board force a player to answer from a specific category, though the player is limited to this constraint for only three unsuccessful turns.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The winner is the first to arrive at Blarney, &amp;quot;and his prize is the life-long gift of eloquence.&amp;quot;&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Ideally the game is for two to six players, though its inventor notes that the game may be played solo. Six cardboard &amp;quot;elves&amp;quot; are provided, but the inventor add that it may also be played by more than six people by adding &amp;quot;shirt buttons or pennies&amp;quot; for the other players to move with.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Finally, the game contains an optional 1-hour tape of Irish music and dance, recorded live during a summer ethnic festival in Baltimore.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
